[0.000, "o", "\r\n\u001b[38;2;142;68;207m\u001b[1m  ━━ NCBI Gene ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    \u001b[2mGene ID               \u001b[0m672\r\n    \u001b[2mSymbol                \u001b[0mBRCA1\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    \u001b[2mFull Name             \u001b[0mBRCA1 DNA repair associated\r\n    \u001b[2mOrganism              \u001b[0mHomo sapiens\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    \u001b[2mChromosome            \u001b[0m17 (17q21.31)\r\n    \u001b[2mType                  \u001b[0mBRCA1 DNA repair associated\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n    \u001b[2mThis gene encodes a 190 kD nuclear phosphoprotein that plays a role in maintaining genomic stability, and it also acts as a tumor suppressor. The BRCA1 gene contains 22 exons spanning about 110 kb of DNA. The encoded protein combines with other tumor suppressors, DNA damage sensors, and signal trans...\u001b[0m\r\n    \u001b[38;2;140;180;255mhttps://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/672\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[38;2;142;68;207m\u001b[1m  ━━ Ensembl ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    \u001b[2mEnsembl ID            \u001b[0mENSG00000012048\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    \u001b[2mBiotype               \u001b[0mprotein_coding\r\n    \u001b[2mLocation              \u001b[0m17:43044292–43170245 (-)\r\n    \u001b[2mAssembly              \u001b[0mGRCh38\r\n    \u001b[2mTranscripts           \u001b[0m47\r\n    \u001b[2mCanonical             \u001b[0mENST00000357654 (protein_coding, 7088 bp)\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    \u001b[38;2;140;180;255mhttps://ensembl.org/Homo_sapiens/Gene/Summary?g=ENSG00000012048\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[38;2;142;68;207m\u001b[1m  ━━ UniProt ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n    \u001b[2mAccession             \u001b[0mP38398\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    \u001b[2mProtein               \u001b[0mBreast cancer type 1 susceptibility protein\r\n    \u001b[2mLength                \u001b[0m1863 aa\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    \u001b[2mStatus                \u001b[0mUniProtKB reviewed (Swiss-Prot)\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    \u001b[2mLocalization          \u001b[0mNucleus, Chromosome, Cytoplasm\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\r\n    \u001b[2mE3 ubiquitin-protein ligase that specifically mediates the formation of 'Lys-6'-linked polyubiquitin chains and plays a central role in DNA repair by facilitating cellular responses to DNA damage (PubMed:10500182, PubMed:12887909, PubMed:12890688, PubMed:14976165, PubMed:16818604, PubMed:17525340, P\u001b[0m\r\n    \u001b[38;2;140;180;255mhttps://www.uniprot.org/uniprotkb/P38398\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[26.228, "o", "\r\n\u001b[38;2;142;68;207m\u001b[1m  ━━ novaflow.ai SYNTHESIS ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    ## BRCA1 — Biological Significance\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    **Core function: homologous recombination repair.** BRCA1 is the master regulator of high-fidelity double-strand break (DSB) repair via homologous recombination (HR). Its 1,863 aa product carries an N-terminal RING domain (E3 ubiquitin ligase activity, dimerizes with BARD1) and tandem C-terminal BRCT domains that bind phospho-Ser/Thr motifs on partners like Abraxas, BACH1/FANCJ, and CtIP. Through these scaffolds BRCA1 assembles the BASC complex, licenses DNA-end resection, and recruits PALB2–BRCA2–RAD51 to drive strand invasion. Loss of BRCA1 forces cells onto error-prone repair (NHEJ, MMEJ), producing the genome-wide instability and characteristic mutational signatures (SBS3, ID6, large deletions with microhomology) seen in BRCA1-null tumors.\r\n    **Tumor suppression and beyond.** BRCA1 enforces the S and G2/M checkpoints, regulates centrosome duplication via Aurora-A, ubiquitinates substrates with K6-linked chains (a non-degradative signal in the damage response), and participates in transcriptional"]
[0.000, "o", " regulation through RNA Pol II and chromatin remodeling. The protein localizes both to nuclear damage foci (53BP1 antagonism for resection commitment) and to centrosomes — so loss yields aneuploidy in addition to point-mutation accumulation. This breadth explains why heterozygous germline loss is sufficient to confer cancer predisposition: the wild-type allele is the rate-limiting tumor suppressor in hormone-sensitive epithelium.\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "    **Clinical relevance.** Germline pathogenic variants in BRCA1 confer ~65–72% lifetime breast cancer risk and ~40–45% ovarian cancer risk, with elevated risk for pancreatic, prostate (in male carriers), and fallopian tube carcinomas. BRCA1-deficient tumors are skewed toward basal-like/triple-negative breast cancer and high-grade serous ovarian cancer. The therapeutically actionable consequence is synthetic lethality with PARP inhibition — olaparib, talazoparib, niraparib, and rucaparib are all approved on this axis. Platinum sensitivity is similarly elevated. HRD score, BRCA1 promoter methylation, and reversion mutations are the principal biomarkers for response and resistance.\r\n    **Experimental implications.** When BRCA1 appears in a hit list, you should: (1) screen for HRD signatures (SBS3, large deletions, LOH score, Myriad HRD or scarHRD) rather than relying on the BRCA1 mutation alone — epigenetic silencing and BRCA1ness phenocopy mutation; (2) check zygosity and LOH at 17q21.31, because mon"]
[0.000, "o", "oallelic loss in tumor often misleads variant callers; (3) flag VUS in the BRCT and RING domains for functional follow-up (SGE data from Findlay et al. 2018 covers most missense calls); (4) in functional assays, use RAD51 foci formation after IR as the gold-standard readout for HR competence, not γH2AX alone.\r\n    **Bottom line.** BRCA1 is the keystone of HR-mediated DSB repair. Its loss is both the etiologic driver of a major fraction of hereditary breast/ovarian cancer and the molecular handle that makes those tumors uniquely treatable with PARP inhibitors and platinum — the cleanest synthetic-lethal axis in clinical oncology today.\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\r\n\u001b[38;5;135m\u001b[1m  ━━ Continue your analysis ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\u001b[0m\r\n"]
